AGI - A human tide - more than two million according to the organizers, 300 thousand for other sources - returned to descend on the streets of Istanbul > against the detention of the mayor of the city, Ekrem Imamoglu, > the president's main opponent, Recep Tayip Erdogan>. Ozgur Ozel, > Secretary of the Republican Party Chp, who candidate Imamoglu against Erdogan at the presidential elections in 2028, had convened the event on March 25, in the Asian district of Maltepe. An appeal to which people responded in mass, confluencing towards the large square from the early hours of the day, from every corner of the city and the surroundings of the metropolis on the Bosphorus. The protest against the president was vehemently and civil at the same time and there were no record of clashes or episodes of violence.
There is a part of the country that believes that the Erdogan cycle has concluded asks a great deal that the country changes the page, led by Imamoglu. The family of the destitute mayor of Istanbul climbed on stage earning the ovation of the crowd >; However, the surprise was the reading of a letter from Imamoglu from prison, with the voice reproduced through artificial intelligence. "These bars represent nothing for me, I have no regrets, indeed I am proud of what was done. It is clear that I am not the one who has to be acquitted, but Erdogan is the one who needs to be cleaned up at all costs," is the message from the prison of Imamoglu, "he is afraid of his opponent, he is embarrassing his supporters > with moves that are everything, less than he tries courage. Even if they try to stop me, I trust you, you are behind me. We laugh at all the false evidence and slanders they want to hit us with."
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Ovation also for the mayor of Ankara, Mansur Yavas>, who has renounced running for the Chp primary precisely for solidarity with Imamoglu. "Every injustice against an opposition leader is a threat to every citizen," Yavas enlisted, and then reiterated that in the presidential election of 2028 Imamoglu will be the candidate of the Chp against Erdogan. The Turkish President must now deal with the boomerang effect of the prison of the mayor of Istanbul >. Not only an opposition that has been recompacted, leaving behind a whole series of controversies that had characterized the last months, but also the anger of the square. The demonstrations that have taken place over the last ten days, beyond the inevitable wars of numbers, represent the biggest protests in Turkey since 2013, when people went to the square against the demolition of the Gezi park.
Prote that, today as then, they left Istanbul and then spread to the rest of the country. If Erdogan was to vote in the next few months, he would be forced to pursue a race which, under these conditions, seems impossible. "The opposition is trying to get us out of illegal means," the president thundered. Words trying to recompact his supporters, although this time they might not be enough. In recent days the Turkish Authority for the elections sanctioned 4 TV channels of the opposition: Tele1, HalkTv, Now (Fox ndr) and SozcuTv. Despite this, all these channels managed to follow today's event, ignored by the media close to the government and the state TV TRT.&nbsp;&nbsp;
